[[ファイル:Yamanashioka shrine Yamanashi-City in the Mt.Ishimori №2.JPG| thumb|200px|Haiden (photographed June 2010)]]
'''Yamanashioka Shrine''' (やまなしおかじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Yamanashi|Q840610|WD=Q840610|1=Yamanashi (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Yamanashi Prefecture|Q132720|WD=Q132720|1=Yamanashi Prefecture}}. It is a former {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|lt=gōsha|1=Gō-sha}} that claims identification with the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} "Yamanashioka Shrine"<ref>However, the common scholarly view identifies the Shikinaisha "Yamanashioka Shrine" with the shrine of the same name in {{ill|lt=Fuefuki|Q849434|WD=Q849434|1=Fuefuki}}, a former gōsha.</ref>.

The shrine stands on a small hill in flat land known as "Ishimori-yama" or "Ishimori-oka"<ref>There is a tradition that {{ill|lt=Daidarabotchi|Q1157529|WD=Q1157529|1=Daidarabotchi}} built it.</ref>. Though compact, the precinct has large trees such as pines and many strange rocks, and is known as a famous spot for {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=azaleas|1=UNKNOWN}}. It was long loved by men of letters, and individual rocks were given distinctive names<ref>It is also pointed out that most of these rocks were once largely buried and only slightly exposed, so it is uncertain whether the site was called "Yamanashioka" at the time of the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' compilation or earlier ("Survey Report").</ref>.

=== Shrine name ===
A folk etymology says the area, being lacking in relief, was called "yama-nashi" (no mountain), which later became "Yamanashi"<ref>"Jinja Meisaichō," quoted in "Survey Report."</ref>. In addition, the '{{ill|lt=Kai Kokushi|Q11577871|WD=Q11577871|1=Kaikokushi}}' of {{ill|lt=Bunka|Q1373146|WD=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1814|Q6943|WD=Q6943|1=1814}}) records the then shrine name as "Kumano Gongen."

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines six {{ill|lt=pillars|Q16283888|WD=Q16283888|lt=pillars|1=pillars}}: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami|WD=Q682306}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kotosakanoo-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hayatamao-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q478504|lt=Kunitokotachi-no-Mikoto|1=Kuni-no-Tokotachi}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi|WD=Q276944}}, and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona|WD=Q3275687}}.

The '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kai Meishōshi|1=UNKNOWN}}' and '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kai Kokushi|1=UNKNOWN}}' of {{ill|lt=Tenmei|Q1194121|WD=Q1194121|1=Tenmei}} 7 ({{ill|lt=1787|Q7763|WD=Q7763|1=1787}}) say the shrine jointly enshrined {{ill|lt=Kumano Gongen|Q11568925|WD=Q11568925|1=Kumano Gongen}} and '''Kunitachi Myōjin'''; the first three deities above correspond to the former, and the latter three to the latter.

=== Origin tradition ===
According to shrine tradition, the original founding year is unknown, but it is said {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yamato Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru|WD=Q461258}} invited the deity during his expedition against the eastern peoples, and one tradition says it was founded by Yamato Takeru in {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|WD=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}} 41 ({{ill|lt=111|Q30640|WD=Q30640|1=AD 111}})<ref name="平凡社">'Shintō Daijiten.'</ref>. East of the honden is the '''Mikoshikake-ishi''', said to be the stone where Yamato Takeru sat. It is further said that in {{ill|lt=Jingo-keiun|Q1373049|WD=Q1373049|1=Jingo-keiun}} 2 ({{ill|lt=768|Q29961|WD=Q29961|1=768}}), {{ill|lt=Sakanoue no Karitamaro|Q3137722|WD=Q3137722|lt=Sakanoue no Karitamaro|1=Sakanoue no Karitamaro}} built shrine buildings; later military figures also rebuilt them repeatedly, including {{ill|lt=Kagami Tōmitsu|Q11399726|WD=Q11399726|1=Kagami Tōmitsu}} in {{ill|lt=Bunji|Q1194415|WD=Q1194415|1=Bunji (era)}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1187|Q19731|WD=Q19731|1=1187}})<ref name="平凡社"/>. In earlier times, a yearly archery rite was also held<ref>'Jinja Meikan.'</ref>.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it held over 2 {{ill|lt=koku|Q855048|WD=Q855048|1=Koku}} 5 {{ill|lt=to|Q1078168|WD=Q1078168|1=To (unit)}} of shuinchi and over 3 koku 7 to of kokuinchi, and in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}) it was ranked gōsha.

=== Subordinate shrines ===
* Tenjin-sha - enshrines Yamato Takeru; stands on top of the above Mikoshikake-ishi.
10 other shrines

=== Shrine architecture ===
The honden is a two-seat {{ill|lt=aiden|Q135009883|WD=Q135009883|1=Aidono}} niken-sha {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} with copper-plate roofing. The {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=moya|1=UNKNOWN}} has gable-side ornamentation such as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=gegyo|1=UNKNOWN}} and board-style {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kaerumata|1=UNKNOWN}}; the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=tokyō|1=UNKNOWN}} are demi-bracket sets with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kobushi-bana|1=UNKNOWN}}; it has an engawa with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=giboshi|1=UNKNOWN}} railings, and rear side panels are {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=waki-shōji|1=UNKNOWN}}. The one-bay {{ill|lt=kōhai|Q11415970|WD=Q11415970|1=kōhai}} uses chamfered square posts and is connected to the moya by an "ebi" {{ill|lt=kōryō|Q124421222|WD=Q124421222|1=kōryō}} beam. Decorative details preserve {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Momoyama-period|1=UNKNOWN}} techniques. It was designated a Yamanashi Prefecture {{ill|lt=tangible cultural property|Q2901860|WD=Q2901860|1=Tangible Cultural Property (Japan)}} on November 7, {{ill|lt=1960|Q3754|WD=Q3754|1=1960}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 35). In dismantling repairs the next year (1961), ink writing found behind a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=daito|1=UNKNOWN}} indicated repair in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 16 ({{ill|lt=1703|Q6822|WD=Q6822|1=1703}}), making it a valuable dated structure<ref>'Yamanashi Prefectural History: Cultural Properties Volume,' Yamanashi Prefecture, 1999.</ref>.

=== Cultural property ===
* Honden (Yamanashi Prefecture designated tangible cultural property)

